I think this has been pointed out before, but note that in Craig's
example the only thing that would prevent SEISMO and CSNET-RELAY
from looping the message back and forth is the value of the preference
field in the MX record (assuming CSNET-RELAY comes back up).  

I ask: do we really have sufficient faith in preference values people
will put in their databases to trust them to prevent this kind of mail
looping?  What if someone forgets that a LOW value means a HIGH
preference?  (Or is it the other way around?)

Peter
